<DOC><DOCNO> AP890512-0205 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-12-89 2209EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-UN-Climate     05-12 0217</FIRST><SECOND>AM-UN-Climate,0222</SECOND><HEAD>U.S. Backs Negotiations on Checking Greenhouse Effect</HEAD><DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The United States on Friday told a U.N.-sponsoredmeeting of experts dealing with climate changes that Washington nowbacked negotiations on a treaty to check the greenhouse effect, aU.N. official reported.   The official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said theUnited States announced it wanted to play a leading part in shapinga coordinated strategy to combat global warming, caused by solarheat trapped under gases in the atmosphere.   He said Washington now strongly backs U.N. initiatives designedto lead to an international convention. Previously, according tothe official, the United States had been not among the majorsupporters.   The meeting in Geneva concluded Friday. It was held under theauspices of the U.N. Environment Program and the WorldMeteorological Organization as part of an 18 month-study ofclimatic changes. The experts will publish their recommendationsnext year.   Scientists fear global temperatures could rise by four to ninedegrees by the year 2050. Such a warming trend could melt polar icecaps and cause sea levels to rise, cause devere droughts and stormsand disrupt the Earth's biological systems.   Scientists will consider the results of Friday's working groupat a meeting of the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change inNairobi, Kenya, next month.</TEXT></DOC>